WEBVTT

1
00:00:13.886 --> 00:00:15.932
Hey.
Pete the plumber.

2
00:00:16.106 --> 00:00:17.368
My hero. Thank you for coming.

3
00:00:17.542 --> 00:00:18.848
Thanks for calling.

4
00:00:19.022 --> 00:00:20.502
On a Sunday. no less.

5
00:00:20.850 --> 00:00:23.156
If leaky pipes don't take
weekends off. why should I?

6
00:00:23.331 --> 00:00:25.898
This one didn't leak.
it nearly exploded.

7
00:00:26.072 --> 00:00:27.639
I managed to shut off the valve.

8
00:00:27.857 --> 00:00:29.598
but I would love to get it fixed
before my husband gets home.

9
00:00:29.772 --> 00:00:31.513
And tries to fix it himself?

10
00:00:31.687 --> 00:00:32.862
Emphasis on the "try."

11
00:00:33.036 --> 00:00:34.342
Yeah. we get that a lot.

12
00:00:34.646 --> 00:00:35.995
It's the bathroom
straight down on the left.

13
00:00:37.562 --> 00:00:40.173
Excuse me.
did I not say no gaming

14
00:00:40.348 --> 00:00:41.958
until your rooms are clean?

15
00:00:42.132 --> 00:00:44.830
Okay. Mom.

16
00:00:49.095 --> 00:00:50.836
It's all done. ma'am.

17
00:00:51.010 --> 00:00:54.579
Sorry it took so long.
Finally got her all fixed.

18
00:00:56.538 --> 00:00:57.408
Ma'am?

19
00:00:57.669 --> 00:01:00.150
Sink's working as good as new.

20
00:01:00.324 --> 00:01:02.848
You want to come check it out?

21
00:01:04.067 --> 00:01:05.198
Ma'am?

22
00:01:06.983 --> 00:01:09.551
What the hell?

23
00:01:44.499 --> 00:01:46.283
<i>I cannot stress enough.</i>

24
00:01:46.457 --> 00:01:48.590
Miss Hines. if this MTAC upgrade
doesn't go perfectly.

25
00:01:48.764 --> 00:01:50.635
heads will roll.
and I don't mean mine.

26
00:01:50.809 --> 00:01:52.202
And I get your meaning. sir.
I do.

27
00:01:52.376 --> 00:01:53.812
Your Multiple Threat
Alert Center

28
00:01:53.986 --> 00:01:55.553
is our most vital fusion hub.

29
00:01:55.814 --> 00:01:57.947
Monitoring threats against
our Navy and our Marines...

30
00:01:58.121 --> 00:02:00.428
I know what MTAC does.
and trust me.

31
00:02:00.602 --> 00:02:02.952
we're working hard to make sure
everything goes without a hitch.

32
00:02:03.126 --> 00:02:06.259
Well. I'm sure whoever last
updated MTAC back in the '90s

33
00:02:06.434 --> 00:02:07.957
worked hard. too. but that

34
00:02:08.261 --> 00:02:09.741
hasn't stopped hackers
from exploiting our weaknesses.

35
00:02:09.915 --> 00:02:11.917
And. apparently.
that was due to a delay

36
00:02:12.091 --> 00:02:13.484
in the firewall reloading.

37
00:02:13.658 --> 00:02:15.268
and we are working hard
to prevent that. too.

38
00:02:15.443 --> 00:02:17.575
Look. I hate to be
such a hard-ass. but

39
00:02:17.836 --> 00:02:19.272
since this upgrade date
was potentially leaked.

40
00:02:19.447 --> 00:02:20.970
we can't be too careful.

41
00:02:21.274 --> 00:02:23.059
Which is precisely why
we're no longer doing that date

42
00:02:23.233 --> 00:02:24.626
and doing the upgrade
tonight instead.

43
00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:26.715
And nobody else
knows about this?

44
00:02:26.889 --> 00:02:28.194
It's 1:00 a.m. on a Sunday.

45
00:02:28.369 --> 00:02:29.718
Hardly anyone knows
we're here. much less

46
00:02:29.892 --> 00:02:31.197
upgrading our entire system.

47
00:02:31.372 --> 00:02:32.982
And where is everyone again?

48
00:02:33.156 --> 00:02:34.375
Most of the agents are at

49
00:02:34.549 --> 00:02:35.767
a seminar in Philly
this weekend.

50
00:02:35.985 --> 00:02:37.116
so my team and I.
we have pretty much

51
00:02:37.290 --> 00:02:38.727
the entire building
to ourselves.

52
00:02:39.641 --> 00:02:42.208
Hey. Kase. Am I too late?

53
00:02:42.383 --> 00:02:44.036
No. no.

54
00:02:44.297 --> 00:02:48.171
- You are here just on time to...
- Help out.

55
00:02:48.345 --> 00:02:49.781
I left the seminar early

56
00:02:50.042 --> 00:02:51.957
- in case you needed moral support.
- Yeah.

57
00:02:52.131 --> 00:02:53.872
- But I-I don't want to interrupt.
- No. you're not.

58
00:02:54.046 --> 00:02:56.527
Special Agent Parker.
this is David Barbado.

59
00:02:56.701 --> 00:02:59.095
- DoD.
- Deputy Chief of Cyber Security.

60
00:02:59.269 --> 00:03:01.184
- Hi. Oh. sorry.
- Parker.

61
00:03:01.358 --> 00:03:02.751
Glad you're here to help.

62
00:03:02.925 --> 00:03:04.100
What? No.

63
00:03:04.361 --> 00:03:05.928
Uh. no. Kasie doesn't
need my help.

64
00:03:06.102 --> 00:03:08.278
that's for sure.
Between her and her cyber team.

65
00:03:08.539 --> 00:03:10.759
MTAC couldn't be
in better hands.

66
00:03:10.933 --> 00:03:12.891
That's exactly what
we're counting on. so

67
00:03:13.152 --> 00:03:15.416
I will leave you to it. then.
Miss Hines.

68
00:03:15.590 --> 00:03:17.418
And just remember...

69
00:03:17.592 --> 00:03:20.203
your country's counting
on you. too.

70
00:03:20.377 --> 00:03:22.727
So. best of luck.

71
00:03:25.426 --> 00:03:26.949
Barbado out.

72
00:03:29.473 --> 00:03:31.170
"Barbado out"?

73
00:03:31.344 --> 00:03:33.042
Dude. I was this close
to convincing him

74
00:03:33.216 --> 00:03:34.565
that no one else
knew about this.

75
00:03:34.739 --> 00:03:37.046
No one else does. except me.
You doing all right?

76
00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:39.440
Yeah. for someone
whose professional future

77
00:03:39.614 --> 00:03:41.833
hangs in the balance.
I'm doing great.

78
00:03:42.094 --> 00:03:44.314
I'm afraid your fancy pastries
aren't gonna help.

79
00:03:44.488 --> 00:03:47.404
Eh. how about some
good old-fashioned donuts?

80
00:03:47.578 --> 00:03:50.320
- Little. uh. emergency
sugar rush couldn't hurt. - Mm-mm.

81
00:03:50.494 --> 00:03:53.497
Mm-mm. No. no. no. Please do not
say emergency. No. Not tonight.

82
00:03:53.671 --> 00:03:56.718
Uh. you heard what Mr. DoD
Cyber Security said.

83
00:03:56.892 --> 00:03:59.198
But you heard what I said.
Look. I know that. uh.

84
00:03:59.372 --> 00:04:01.723
rebooting our whole entire
system here is a big job.

85
00:04:01.897 --> 00:04:04.160
but you and your tech trolls
are up to it.

86
00:04:04.334 --> 00:04:06.118
Yeah. my tech trolls.
Don't I wish.

87
00:04:06.292 --> 00:04:07.293
What. they're not?

88
00:04:07.468 --> 00:04:09.295
Well. for security purposes.

89
00:04:09.470 --> 00:04:12.690
DoD assigned me cyber techs
from four separate agencies.

90
00:04:12.864 --> 00:04:14.562
All very highly qualified.
but man.

91
00:04:14.736 --> 00:04:16.781
after a week together. you know.
they really lack enthusiasm.

92
00:04:16.955 --> 00:04:19.131
Maybe they could use
a sugar rush.

93
00:04:19.392 --> 00:04:21.351
Well. they're in my lab.
By all means. please.

94
00:04:21.612 --> 00:04:23.658
Oh. and by the way.
don't call them tech trolls.

95
00:04:23.832 --> 00:04:26.008
They're also supersensitive.

96
00:04:30.273 --> 00:04:32.275
Wow. I don't think
I've ever seen

97
00:04:32.449 --> 00:04:33.972
a dozen disappear that fast.

98
00:04:34.146 --> 00:04:37.062
Sorry. It's just. no one
ever brings us donuts.

99
00:04:37.236 --> 00:04:38.934
Like Lewis Latimer. or

100
00:04:39.108 --> 00:04:40.718
Granville Woods.
our contributions

101
00:04:40.979 --> 00:04:42.459
- too often go unappreciated.
- Don't mind Felix or you'll

102
00:04:42.633 --> 00:04:44.417
spend days looking up
obscure references.

103
00:04:44.592 --> 00:04:46.158
So many idiots out there.

104
00:04:46.332 --> 00:04:47.847
Where do these people come from?

105
00:04:48.021 --> 00:04:50.075
Anyway. I just wanted to say hi.

106
00:04:50.249 --> 00:04:51.729
make sure everybody's
on the same page.

107
00:04:51.903 --> 00:04:53.078
I know Kasie's excited.

108
00:04:53.252 --> 00:04:55.080
Oh. us. too. Agent Parker.

109
00:04:55.254 --> 00:04:56.560
Definitely.

110
00:04:56.821 --> 00:04:58.388
I'd say Kasie's
even more than excited.

111
00:04:58.562 --> 00:05:00.477
She's downright...
What is the word?

112
00:05:00.651 --> 00:05:02.261
- It kind of means. like... - Um...
- Effusive.

113
00:05:02.435 --> 00:05:04.786
- That's it. yes. She's effusive.
- That's a great word for it.

114
00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:06.396
Uh. bossy's a better one.

115
00:05:06.570 --> 00:05:07.876
Really. Daryl?

116
00:05:08.050 --> 00:05:09.965
Sorry. No filter. this guy.

117
00:05:10.139 --> 00:05:12.402
Not to mention issues
with assertive women.

118
00:05:12.663 --> 00:05:14.143
You know what I'm saying.
Kasie just needs to trust

119
00:05:14.317 --> 00:05:15.840
that we know what we're doing
and just let us do it.

120
00:05:16.014 --> 00:05:17.755
Idiot.

121
00:05:19.540 --> 00:05:21.846
Not Kasie.
This idiot.

122
00:05:22.020 --> 00:05:24.893
Uh. would it help to know
that Kasie is getting

123
00:05:25.154 --> 00:05:27.156
tremendous pressure from above?

124
00:05:27.330 --> 00:05:29.288
Not to mention the pressure
she already puts on herself.

125
00:05:29.462 --> 00:05:31.464
Really? I'm sorry to hear that.

126
00:05:31.639 --> 00:05:35.251
"No pressure. no diamonds."

127
00:05:35.425 --> 00:05:37.340
Thomas Carlyle? Philosopher?

128
00:05:37.514 --> 00:05:40.256
Here's the thing. uh. Kasie's
just like the rest of us.

129
00:05:40.517 --> 00:05:43.302
She's just trying to do her best
the best way she knows how.

130
00:05:44.913 --> 00:05:46.262
<i>Donut break's over.</i>

131
00:05:46.567 --> 00:05:48.003
<i>Time to hit your
battle stations. people.</i>

132
00:05:49.482 --> 00:05:52.050
Uh... On my way. Kase.

133
00:05:52.964 --> 00:05:56.098
As you know. the upgrade
will shut down not only MTAC.

134
00:05:56.272 --> 00:05:57.839
but all computers. land lines.

135
00:05:58.013 --> 00:06:01.233
and security cameras
for two hours.

136
00:06:01.407 --> 00:06:02.626
During which time.

137
00:06:02.974 --> 00:06:04.541
we will monitor progress
from our workstations

138
00:06:04.715 --> 00:06:06.587
and communicate via headset

139
00:06:06.848 --> 00:06:08.458
as the system reboots.

140
00:06:08.719 --> 00:06:10.547
Once again. thank you in advance

141
00:06:10.721 --> 00:06:12.767
for your immeasurable
contribution

142
00:06:12.941 --> 00:06:15.944
to NCIS. to the security
of the nation.

143
00:06:16.118 --> 00:06:18.337
and to the world.

144
00:06:21.123 --> 00:06:21.819
I didn't miss it.
I didn't miss it.

145
00:06:21.993 --> 00:06:23.038
Kase.

146
00:06:23.212 --> 00:06:25.344
Kase. Did I miss it?

147
00:06:25.518 --> 00:06:26.607
Timing's perfect. Jimmy.

148
00:06:26.781 --> 00:06:28.217
Okay. I totally forgot

149
00:06:28.478 --> 00:06:30.132
that Kasie moved
the system reboot to tonight.

150
00:06:30.306 --> 00:06:32.134
Yeah. and I don't recall
telling you.

151
00:06:32.395 --> 00:06:35.528
So. what? You ran here?
Why are you so sweaty?

152
00:06:35.703 --> 00:06:37.792
Oh. gosh. There's no time for
that now. It is time to light

153
00:06:37.966 --> 00:06:40.011
this candle in T-minus five.

154
00:06:40.185 --> 00:06:41.317
four.

155
00:06:41.491 --> 00:06:43.058
three. two...

156
00:06:43.232 --> 00:06:45.887
and... one.

157
00:06:46.844 --> 00:06:49.630
- No turning back now.
- Nah. nah.

158
00:06:49.804 --> 00:06:51.196
You got this. Kase.

159
00:06:51.457 --> 00:06:53.198
Just think of it as one big
smartphone reboot.

160
00:06:53.372 --> 00:06:56.158
Except the. uh. security
of the entire Western world

161
00:06:56.332 --> 00:06:59.465
does not rely on us
upgrading our phones.

162
00:06:59.727 --> 00:07:01.380
Can you go breathe
somewhere else?

163
00:07:01.554 --> 00:07:03.600
Yeah. yeah. All right.

164
00:07:03.774 --> 00:07:06.864
Again. Jimmy. did you run here?

165
00:07:07.125 --> 00:07:08.344
Oh. no. no. no.
I just come in sometimes

166
00:07:08.605 --> 00:07:10.215
on Sunday nights.
catch up on paperwork.

167
00:07:10.389 --> 00:07:12.130
you know. when I can't sleep.
Like-like tonight.

168
00:07:12.304 --> 00:07:13.784
It's a good thing. too.
because. uh. otherwise.

169
00:07:13.958 --> 00:07:15.568
I would've missed all of this.

170
00:07:15.743 --> 00:07:18.180
So... the sweat?

171
00:07:18.354 --> 00:07:19.790
What sweat? Oh. this sweat...

172
00:07:20.095 --> 00:07:21.400
- the sweat that's on me right now?
- Uh-huh.

173
00:07:21.574 --> 00:07:24.447
Uh. well. it's 'cause
the AC down in autopsy

174
00:07:24.621 --> 00:07:26.057
is on the fritz again. you know.

175
00:07:26.231 --> 00:07:28.320
so we got a hot autopsy
on our hands.

176
00:07:28.581 --> 00:07:30.671
And that-that-that. that sounds
like that's made-up.

177
00:07:30.845 --> 00:07:32.194
That's not made-up. though.

178
00:07:32.455 --> 00:07:34.457
I am overdue for a check-in.

179
00:07:34.631 --> 00:07:36.111
Okay. here we go.

180
00:07:36.285 --> 00:07:37.678
And we have liftoff. people.

181
00:07:37.852 --> 00:07:39.680
Let's get some status reports.

182
00:07:39.941 --> 00:07:41.203
<i>How is our PowerShell. Harold?</i>

183
00:07:41.377 --> 00:07:42.944
Sorry. one second.

184
00:07:43.118 --> 00:07:45.381
PowerShell script
is good. Kasie.

185
00:07:45.555 --> 00:07:48.123
Great.
Nadine. our ISO signature?

186
00:07:48.297 --> 00:07:51.169
ISO signature is humming.
buffers are clean.

187
00:07:51.343 --> 00:07:53.606
- caches are happy.
<i>- Love it.</i>

188
00:07:53.781 --> 00:07:55.391
How about MD5. Felix?

189
00:07:55.652 --> 00:07:58.220
MD5 is pristine. No bad blocks.

190
00:07:58.394 --> 00:08:00.962
We are rebooting like a dream.

191
00:08:01.136 --> 00:08:04.095
Nice. Okay. how about
our processor cores. Daryl?

192
00:08:05.836 --> 00:08:07.185
<i>Talk to me. Daryl.
Are the PCs breathing</i>

193
00:08:07.446 --> 00:08:09.144
or screaming?

194
00:08:09.405 --> 00:08:10.885
Daryl?

195
00:08:11.146 --> 00:08:13.322
Daryl. where are you?

196
00:08:14.497 --> 00:08:15.890
<i>Daryl. come in.</i>

197
00:08:16.151 --> 00:08:17.848
<i>Talk to me. Daryl?</i>

198
00:08:26.465 --> 00:08:28.119
...seven. eight. nine.

199
00:08:28.293 --> 00:08:31.079
Come on. Daryl.
Come on. breathe.

200
00:08:32.036 --> 00:08:33.995
- Breathe.
- All right. Jimmy?

201
00:08:34.169 --> 00:08:35.474
Jimmy.

202
00:08:35.648 --> 00:08:37.563
It's okay. You tried.

203
00:08:37.738 --> 00:08:39.174
Call it.

204
00:08:39.348 --> 00:08:40.784
I just don't get it.

205
00:08:41.089 --> 00:08:42.264
I mean. he was alive and well
on the MTAC screen.

206
00:08:42.438 --> 00:08:44.092
w-what. ten minutes ago?

207
00:08:44.396 --> 00:08:46.355
Could he have just tripped and
hit his head on the way down?

208
00:08:46.529 --> 00:08:48.313
Uh. I mean. yeah. o-of course.
it's possible.

209
00:08:48.487 --> 00:08:50.272
What about maybe a seizure?
An aneurysm?

210
00:08:50.446 --> 00:08:52.274
I don't know. I-I got to get him
down to autopsy

211
00:08:52.448 --> 00:08:54.929
- before I can answer that.
- Hold on. hold on.

212
00:08:55.190 --> 00:08:56.321
Let's not move him yet.

213
00:08:56.495 --> 00:08:59.020
Just in case. You know?

214
00:08:59.194 --> 00:09:02.066
- Wait. s-so. you're thinking maybe...
- I don't know what I think.

215
00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:04.634
But until we can process
the room for clues.

216
00:09:04.808 --> 00:09:06.592
no one comes in or out.

217
00:09:07.942 --> 00:09:09.508
<i>You guys find Daryl?</i>

218
00:09:09.682 --> 00:09:11.510
<i>Is he okay?</i>

219
00:09:13.817 --> 00:09:17.386
But how did he fall? And did
he just fall? What happened?

220
00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:20.824
Jimmy is giving him a prelim
in autopsy to figure that out.

221
00:09:21.085 --> 00:09:23.914
Okay. well. of all the things
I worried about going wrong.

222
00:09:24.088 --> 00:09:26.221
Daryl dropping dead was
not one of them.

223
00:09:26.395 --> 00:09:28.484
All right.
Considering the circumstances.

224
00:09:28.745 --> 00:09:31.443
you think maybe
we call off the upgrade?

225
00:09:31.617 --> 00:09:33.097
I would love to.
but it is too late.

226
00:09:33.271 --> 00:09:34.751
Doing so would damage files.

227
00:09:35.012 --> 00:09:36.187
destroy employee records.

228
00:09:36.361 --> 00:09:37.754
- damage data history...
- Okay.

229
00:09:38.059 --> 00:09:40.104
we keep it going.
and we'll process your office

230
00:09:40.278 --> 00:09:42.150
- as soon as it's done.
- I-I'll have to reshuffle

231
00:09:42.324 --> 00:09:44.282
the tech trolls to get it right.

232
00:09:44.456 --> 00:09:45.718
God. what do I even tell them?

233
00:09:45.893 --> 00:09:47.111
You don't. Not yet.

234
00:09:47.329 --> 00:09:48.721
I mean. if they know
that Daryl is dead.

235
00:09:48.896 --> 00:09:50.593
good luck getting them
to focus again.

236
00:09:50.767 --> 00:09:52.464
Well. what am I supposed to say?

237
00:09:53.683 --> 00:09:56.164
Anything. Besides the truth.

238
00:09:57.034 --> 00:09:58.209
Food poisoning?

239
00:09:58.470 --> 00:09:59.645
- Mm-hmm.
- It was those donuts.

240
00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:00.951
wasn't it?

241
00:10:01.125 --> 00:10:02.866
I feel queasy
and I only had one.

242
00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:04.215
You had two.

243
00:10:04.476 --> 00:10:05.913
- Sorry.
- Well. Daryl had four. So...

244
00:10:06.087 --> 00:10:07.479
You know what?
It wasn't the donuts. guys.

245
00:10:07.653 --> 00:10:09.699
Daryl thinks he had
some bad sushi at lunch.

246
00:10:09.873 --> 00:10:12.223
- He is resting in autopsy now.
- Autopsy?

247
00:10:12.397 --> 00:10:14.356
Where our Dr. Palmer
is taking great care of him.

248
00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:16.271
Uh. he's gonna be just fine.

249
00:10:16.445 --> 00:10:17.925
But in the meantime.
we just. we need to reshuffle

250
00:10:18.099 --> 00:10:19.274
some responsibilities.

251
00:10:19.448 --> 00:10:21.972
Mm-hmm. Okay.
Well. then. obviously.

252
00:10:22.146 --> 00:10:23.800
you're gonna want me
to take over Daryl's place.

253
00:10:23.974 --> 00:10:25.541
where I should have been
from the beginning.

254
00:10:25.715 --> 00:10:27.630
Oh. actually. we're gonna put
Nadine on power cores.

255
00:10:27.804 --> 00:10:29.719
Oh. We're playing favorites.

256
00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:32.461
What? No.
I-I need you on MD5. Felix.

257
00:10:32.635 --> 00:10:34.855
so I can take over
ISO signature for Nadine.

258
00:10:35.116 --> 00:10:36.204
who's going to take over
from Daryl.

259
00:10:36.378 --> 00:10:37.422
No favorites here.

260
00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:39.555
Actually.
I would be better on MD5

261
00:10:39.729 --> 00:10:41.905
if Felix wants
to take over PowerShell.

262
00:10:42.079 --> 00:10:43.733
I wouldn't touch your PowerShell

263
00:10:43.994 --> 00:10:45.169
- with the spear of Cú Chulainn.
- Okay.

264
00:10:45.343 --> 00:10:46.779
I minored
in Irish mythology. Felix.

265
00:10:46.954 --> 00:10:48.216
- I know what that means.
- Do you?

266
00:10:48.477 --> 00:10:50.348
- Yes. and it's "Coo-coo-lan."
- No. no. no.

267
00:10:50.609 --> 00:10:52.437
- Yes. it is. "Cú Chulainn."
- No. it's "Cu-cullen." "Cú Chulainn."

268
00:10:52.611 --> 00:10:54.135
People. enough. please.

269
00:10:54.309 --> 00:10:58.095
Can we just play nice
for the sake of the upgrade?

270
00:10:59.053 --> 00:11:03.144
Nadine? Enjoy PCs.

271
00:11:03.318 --> 00:11:05.059
- Thank you.
- All right.

272
00:11:05.973 --> 00:11:09.019
I'm sorry. he's just... Sorry.

273
00:11:10.194 --> 00:11:11.239
Boys.

274
00:11:11.413 --> 00:11:13.284
Not the word that I had in mind.

275
00:11:15.373 --> 00:11:17.332
Hey. is this your laptop
or Daryl's sitting here?

276
00:11:17.506 --> 00:11:20.161
Yes. that's mine. Thanks.

277
00:11:21.031 --> 00:11:22.859
<i>Kasie. got a minute?</i>

278
00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:24.600
Yes.

279
00:11:25.340 --> 00:11:27.255
What's the word?

280
00:11:27.516 --> 00:11:29.561
Parker. you were supposed
to stay in MTAC.

281
00:11:29.735 --> 00:11:32.086
MTAC is fine.
Someone else is not.

282
00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:33.783
Now. mind you.
I can't run any X-rays

283
00:11:33.957 --> 00:11:35.437
with our computers down.
but Daryl's neck

284
00:11:35.611 --> 00:11:38.222
sure feels broken to me.
along with a skull fracture.

285
00:11:38.396 --> 00:11:40.616
Oh. gosh. all this
just from a fall?

286
00:11:40.877 --> 00:11:42.966
Well. not "just."
No. the bruising that emerged

287
00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:44.968
across the jawline here suggests
he was struck pretty hard

288
00:11:45.229 --> 00:11:48.058
- before his head hit the floor.
- Struck? By who?

289
00:11:48.232 --> 00:11:51.496
Uh. one of his
fellow trolls. maybe?

290
00:11:51.670 --> 00:11:53.107
Oh. come on.

291
00:11:53.411 --> 00:11:54.760
They may be a bunch
of socially awkward malcontents.

292
00:11:54.935 --> 00:11:56.675
but...

293
00:11:57.024 --> 00:11:58.547
- You know. come to think of it...
- It was either them

294
00:11:58.721 --> 00:11:59.852
or someone else in the building.

295
00:12:00.114 --> 00:12:01.942
Uh. uh. security.
cleaning staff.

296
00:12:02.116 --> 00:12:04.770
I'll have base police
lock down the Navy Yard.

297
00:12:05.554 --> 00:12:09.471
Someone just moved my yoga mat
down in Ducky's MPR.

298
00:12:09.645 --> 00:12:11.647
How could you
possibly know that?

299
00:12:11.908 --> 00:12:12.953
'Cause it came with this app.

300
00:12:13.214 --> 00:12:14.476
Tells me the location of my mat.

301
00:12:14.650 --> 00:12:16.043
temperatures. moisture levels.

302
00:12:16.217 --> 00:12:17.783
Moisture levels?

303
00:12:17.958 --> 00:12:21.657
Do you want anyone else
sweating on your yoga mat?

304
00:12:21.831 --> 00:12:23.311
- Ugh. who would?
- I do not want that. no.

305
00:12:23.572 --> 00:12:25.487
No. more importantly.
who moved it?

306
00:12:25.748 --> 00:12:27.750
Maybe it's the same person
that did that.

307
00:12:27.924 --> 00:12:30.144
There's only one way
to find out.

308
00:12:30.405 --> 00:12:32.407
You stick with Kasie.
I'll be back.

309
00:12:43.853 --> 00:12:45.855
Jimmy. I said stick with Kasie.

310
00:12:46.029 --> 00:12:47.248
And she's locked safely in MTAC.

311
00:12:47.422 --> 00:12:48.814
You need someone
watching your back.

312
00:12:49.076 --> 00:12:50.251
I mean. you guys
always travel in pairs. right?

313
00:12:50.425 --> 00:12:51.513
- So. I thought...
- Okay.

314
00:12:51.687 --> 00:12:53.167
Okay... okay. Fine.

315
00:12:54.603 --> 00:12:55.996
You hear that?

316
00:12:56.170 --> 00:12:57.649
It could be Henry.

317
00:12:57.823 --> 00:13:00.609
The ghost? Please. not now.

318
00:13:06.049 --> 00:13:07.268
- Wh... Oh. God!
- Tommy.

319
00:13:07.442 --> 00:13:09.618
Agent Parker. Jimmy.
You scared me.

320
00:13:09.792 --> 00:13:12.447
- Well. that makes three of us.
- What are you doing down here?

321
00:13:12.621 --> 00:13:13.970
I'm making my rounds.

322
00:13:14.144 --> 00:13:15.319
Heard a noise
coming from Ducky's.

323
00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:16.842
I thought it might
just be Henry.

324
00:13:17.017 --> 00:13:18.279
Again with Henry.

325
00:13:18.453 --> 00:13:19.976
But it was just you guys.

326
00:13:20.150 --> 00:13:21.717
My... my heart. oh. man.

327
00:13:23.632 --> 00:13:25.721
- That wasn't Henry.
- All right. stay here. Tom.

328
00:13:25.895 --> 00:13:28.463
- Do you want my. uh...
- No.

329
00:13:38.081 --> 00:13:40.388
I knew I should have gone
to a hotel.

330
00:13:40.562 --> 00:13:42.520
Sam?

331
00:13:43.826 --> 00:13:45.915
I guess I should've called. huh?

332
00:13:55.142 --> 00:13:57.405
Sam Hanna? What the heck?

333
00:13:57.579 --> 00:14:00.016
- It's good to see you. too. Kasie.
- Oh. gosh.

334
00:14:00.277 --> 00:14:01.322
Hey. what brings you here?

335
00:14:01.496 --> 00:14:03.411
My worst-kept-secret
MTAC upgrade.

336
00:14:03.672 --> 00:14:05.065
or do you just. like.

337
00:14:05.413 --> 00:14:06.892
magically appear whenever
somebody mysteriously dies?

338
00:14:07.067 --> 00:14:08.938
No magic. As I was
just telling the fellas.

339
00:14:09.199 --> 00:14:11.071
I had a long layover on my way
to visit a buddy in Dubai.

340
00:14:11.245 --> 00:14:13.899
and I figured I'd catch a few
winks on Ducky's MPR couch.

341
00:14:14.161 --> 00:14:16.337
I just wish we'd known.

342
00:14:16.511 --> 00:14:18.556
I-It just... because Victoria.

343
00:14:18.730 --> 00:14:21.559
she's gonna be so disappointed
to know that you were in town.

344
00:14:21.733 --> 00:14:23.518
- you didn't at least call.
- Jimmy.

345
00:14:23.692 --> 00:14:25.041
it was a last-minute
flight delay.

346
00:14:25.215 --> 00:14:27.217
I'll be sure to call
Crown Vic just the same.

347
00:14:27.391 --> 00:14:29.306
Yeah. we're all happy to see
you. Sam. but does anybody mind

348
00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:31.656
if we get back to finding
our tech troll killer?

349
00:14:31.830 --> 00:14:33.310
Well. I don't mind
forgoing my couch time

350
00:14:33.571 --> 00:14:35.182
- to help out if you need.
- Hey. more the merrier.

351
00:14:35.356 --> 00:14:36.357
All right. Kasie
will stick with the reboot.

352
00:14:36.531 --> 00:14:37.749
Sam and I will search

353
00:14:38.010 --> 00:14:39.490
the building
for any additional workers

354
00:14:39.664 --> 00:14:42.189
and then question them
along with the tech trolls.

355
00:14:42.363 --> 00:14:43.625
Man with a plan.

356
00:14:43.886 --> 00:14:45.453
Uh. w-wait. hold on.
Where am I in that plan?

357
00:14:45.627 --> 00:14:47.933
I assumed you had autopsy stuff.

358
00:14:48.108 --> 00:14:49.326
Not without computer access.

359
00:14:49.587 --> 00:14:51.111
I can't really do much
down there. Uh...

360
00:14:51.372 --> 00:14:53.069
But-but there are three
remaining tech trolls. so...

361
00:14:53.243 --> 00:14:55.767
You know. you should've seen him
in Hawaii. in that dungeon

362
00:14:56.028 --> 00:14:58.509
they had us in. Parker.
I mean... man's got skills.

363
00:14:58.683 --> 00:14:59.945
I never said he didn't.

364
00:15:00.250 --> 00:15:01.208
All right. Jimmy makes it
three on three.

365
00:15:01.382 --> 00:15:02.600
so let's see
what everyone knows.

366
00:15:02.774 --> 00:15:04.559
What about not scaring them?

367
00:15:04.733 --> 00:15:07.257
Kind of told everybody
that Daryl had food poisoning.

368
00:15:07.431 --> 00:15:08.911
Uh. okay. then. let's go with that.

369
00:15:09.085 --> 00:15:11.653
Daryl is not dead.
he's just sick.

370
00:15:11.914 --> 00:15:13.394
Okay. and to be clear.

371
00:15:13.698 --> 00:15:15.091
we're not interrogating them.
we're just wh... uh. what.

372
00:15:15.265 --> 00:15:17.833
- feeling them out. or...?
- A friendly chat.

373
00:15:18.007 --> 00:15:19.400
And if it wasn't premeditated.

374
00:15:19.617 --> 00:15:21.315
then our killer
might just give it up easy.

375
00:15:21.489 --> 00:15:23.055
We'll divvy them up.
keep it friendly.

376
00:15:23.230 --> 00:15:24.709
compare notes afterwards.

377
00:15:24.883 --> 00:15:26.233
Hey. Sam. hey.

378
00:15:26.407 --> 00:15:27.973
Thanks for having my back there.

379
00:15:28.148 --> 00:15:30.628
You think. uh.
Victoria will forgive me

380
00:15:30.889 --> 00:15:32.282
for not calling. Jimmy?

381
00:15:32.543 --> 00:15:34.806
Okay. okay. you...

382
00:15:35.590 --> 00:15:37.896
Just saying.
you could text a guy. Come on.

383
00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:41.248
I know you didn't bake the
donuts. but you did bring them.

384
00:15:41.422 --> 00:15:44.164
And they didn't give Daryl
food poisoning. Nadine.

385
00:15:44.338 --> 00:15:45.426
I can promise you.

386
00:15:45.600 --> 00:15:46.775
So. he's okay?

387
00:15:47.036 --> 00:15:48.820
You seem to care
a lot about him.

388
00:15:48.994 --> 00:15:50.300
I care if he's got something
I might catch.

389
00:15:50.474 --> 00:15:52.041
I practically bleached
this keyboard

390
00:15:52.215 --> 00:15:53.216
after he used it.

391
00:15:53.390 --> 00:15:55.914
So. you didn't know Daryl well?

392
00:15:56.872 --> 00:15:58.134
Before he got sick. I mean.

393
00:15:58.308 --> 00:16:00.267
You-you don't know Daryl well?

394
00:16:00.441 --> 00:16:03.357
No. I keep things professional
with my coworkers.

395
00:16:03.531 --> 00:16:05.010
Which is not that hard
with Daryl.

396
00:16:05.185 --> 00:16:07.491
He goes heavy on the body spray.

397
00:16:07.665 --> 00:16:08.710
I have yet to give Daryl
enough thought

398
00:16:08.884 --> 00:16:10.364
to form an opinion either way.

399
00:16:10.625 --> 00:16:12.192
Neither affinity nor contempt.

400
00:16:12.453 --> 00:16:15.673
So. safe to say you didn't have
any shared interests.

401
00:16:15.934 --> 00:16:17.022
career goals?

402
00:16:17.197 --> 00:16:18.850
With Daryl?

403
00:16:19.111 --> 00:16:20.939
Please. He'd be incapable

404
00:16:21.113 --> 00:16:22.811
of having
a like-minded discourse.

405
00:16:22.985 --> 00:16:26.597
From wave-particle duality
to loop quantum gravity.

406
00:16:26.771 --> 00:16:29.078
the-the man would be
completely out of his depth.

407
00:16:29.252 --> 00:16:31.515
Sure. yeah.
I mean. who wouldn't be?

408
00:16:31.689 --> 00:16:33.213
I mean. let's be honest.
that'd be like

409
00:16:33.430 --> 00:16:36.172
me trying to explain to you
autolysis or adipocere

410
00:16:36.346 --> 00:16:39.567
or any other facet
of forensic taphonomy.

411
00:16:39.741 --> 00:16:41.351
Sure.

412
00:16:42.178 --> 00:16:43.658
Kind of. Yeah.

413
00:16:43.832 --> 00:16:45.050
I'm Special Agent Sam Hanna.

414
00:16:45.312 --> 00:16:47.923
It's so nice
to meet you. Sam. and...

415
00:16:48.097 --> 00:16:50.534
I cannot tell you
how sorry I am.

416
00:16:52.275 --> 00:16:53.668
Well. lay it on me.

417
00:16:53.842 --> 00:16:54.930
Sorry about what?

418
00:16:55.104 --> 00:16:57.149
A-About Daryl getting sick.

419
00:16:57.324 --> 00:17:00.414
I know he seems preoccupied
with his online debates. but...

420
00:17:00.588 --> 00:17:03.243
this job means as much to him
as it does me.

421
00:17:03.417 --> 00:17:05.419
How much does it mean to you?

422
00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:08.160
Positions like this.
they don't grow on trees.

423
00:17:08.335 --> 00:17:10.162
Competition is fierce.

424
00:17:10.337 --> 00:17:11.816
Though I appreciate
Kasie's faith in me.

425
00:17:12.077 --> 00:17:14.254
I would much rather be
monitoring the processor cores

426
00:17:14.428 --> 00:17:16.778
from home with Bradley Cooper.

427
00:17:16.952 --> 00:17:18.127
I...

428
00:17:18.301 --> 00:17:20.216
Wait. so... I'm sorry. the actor?

429
00:17:20.390 --> 00:17:23.045
Oh. my God. he's beautiful.
Do you want to see a picture?

430
00:17:23.915 --> 00:17:26.266
Sure.

431
00:17:26.527 --> 00:17:28.964
Oh. my beautiful baby.
am I right?

432
00:17:29.138 --> 00:17:31.271
Yep. that's one handsome spider.

433
00:17:31.532 --> 00:17:34.448
Um. but again. back to Daryl?

434
00:17:34.622 --> 00:17:36.841
Daryl is no different
than Harold or Felix.

435
00:17:37.015 --> 00:17:39.670
They seem like
competitive schoolboys.

436
00:17:39.844 --> 00:17:41.933
but it's just a mask
for their insecurity.

437
00:17:42.107 --> 00:17:46.503
So. Felix. was there any part
of you that wanted Daryl's job?

438
00:17:46.677 --> 00:17:49.767
Of course I wanted Daryl's job.
I'm infinitely more qualified.

439
00:17:49.941 --> 00:17:52.814
Did you want it bad enough
to fight him for it?

440
00:17:52.988 --> 00:17:54.729
Fight him? What...

441
00:17:54.903 --> 00:17:56.383
What are we. troglodytes?

442
00:17:56.557 --> 00:17:57.558
So. you know Daryl well. then.

443
00:17:57.732 --> 00:17:59.211
Well enough.

444
00:17:59.386 --> 00:18:01.649
We met back in college. At Penn.

445
00:18:01.823 --> 00:18:04.956
UPenn. Impressive.

446
00:18:05.130 --> 00:18:06.871
Wha... what am I saying?

447
00:18:07.045 --> 00:18:08.438
Cornell.

448
00:18:08.612 --> 00:18:11.528
Sorry. sorry.
We-we went to Cornell together.

449
00:18:12.181 --> 00:18:14.052
You forgot
where you went to college?

450
00:18:14.226 --> 00:18:16.403
Wha...

451
00:18:16.577 --> 00:18:18.709
No. i-it's just
my lifelong bitterness

452
00:18:18.883 --> 00:18:22.931
at not being accepted by Penn
that will never not sting.

453
00:18:23.105 --> 00:18:24.411
So. Cornell. then.

454
00:18:24.585 --> 00:18:26.587
Yeah. yeah. Cornell.

455
00:18:26.761 --> 00:18:28.589
I loved it. Yeah. it was great.

456
00:18:28.763 --> 00:18:32.114
And it's <i>gorges.</i>

457
00:18:32.288 --> 00:18:34.551
Because Cornell's in Ithaca.

458
00:18:34.725 --> 00:18:37.859
where there's a lot of.
uh. gorges.

459
00:18:38.033 --> 00:18:39.904
<i>Gorges.</i>

460
00:18:40.078 --> 00:18:41.166
Yeah.

461
00:18:41.515 --> 00:18:42.646
...and the crew were here

462
00:18:42.820 --> 00:18:44.605
before you came in
for overnight.

463
00:18:44.779 --> 00:18:46.911
- What'd you find out?
- I checked the gate log. Agent Parker.

464
00:18:47.085 --> 00:18:49.479
No one's exited
the Navy Yard since 0102.

465
00:18:49.653 --> 00:18:51.307
Right after the reboot started.

466
00:18:51.481 --> 00:18:54.223
Last to leave was a member
of the custodial staff.

467
00:18:54.397 --> 00:18:55.833
Vito Gironda.

468
00:18:56.094 --> 00:18:57.400
Yeah. lucky Vito.

469
00:18:57.661 --> 00:18:59.446
I drew the short straw
on the overnight shift.

470
00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:01.143
Uh. at least
the overtime's nice.

471
00:19:01.317 --> 00:19:02.536
Yeah. I hear that.

472
00:19:02.710 --> 00:19:03.972
All right.
thanks for your time. Tommy.

473
00:19:04.146 --> 00:19:05.930
Thanks. Petty Officer.
Uh. Tommy.

474
00:19:06.104 --> 00:19:07.454
Um. this Vito?

475
00:19:07.628 --> 00:19:08.803
Do you happen to have
his number handy?

476
00:19:08.977 --> 00:19:10.935
Oh. yeah.
Must have it here somewhere.

477
00:19:12.328 --> 00:19:13.547
If you don't mind me asking. uh.

478
00:19:13.808 --> 00:19:15.897
is this about
those computer geeks?

479
00:19:16.724 --> 00:19:17.942
What makes you think that?

480
00:19:18.116 --> 00:19:19.901
Uh. not for nothing.
but I was mopping

481
00:19:20.075 --> 00:19:22.077
near that subbasement
they work in.

482
00:19:22.251 --> 00:19:25.123
uh. after Vito went home.
and I-I don't know. I...

483
00:19:25.297 --> 00:19:28.344
heard a whole lot of bickering.
you know?

484
00:19:28.518 --> 00:19:30.041
- Oh. here it is.
- Bickering?

485
00:19:30.215 --> 00:19:31.913
Yeah. About what. I can't say.

486
00:19:32.087 --> 00:19:34.655
but. uh. Kasie deserves
a better crew than that.

487
00:19:36.308 --> 00:19:37.919
Uh. that's the wife.
I-I got to take this.

488
00:19:38.093 --> 00:19:40.008
Uh. if I can be any help.
just holler.

489
00:19:40.182 --> 00:19:41.226
All right.

490
00:19:41.401 --> 00:19:42.576
- Hey.
- How you doing?

491
00:19:42.750 --> 00:19:44.099
Hate to say it. but. uh.

492
00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:45.709
neither Harold nor Felix
gave us much.

493
00:19:45.883 --> 00:19:47.494
Other than a pair
of matching headaches.

494
00:19:47.668 --> 00:19:49.060
Same with Nadine.

495
00:19:49.365 --> 00:19:52.020
All I got was. uh.
a spider named Bradley Cooper.

496
00:19:52.194 --> 00:19:54.588
and apparently Daryl wore
too much body spray.

497
00:19:54.762 --> 00:19:56.067
Man. they can talk.

498
00:19:56.241 --> 00:19:58.200
And argue. according to Tommy.

499
00:19:58.374 --> 00:19:59.593
They definitely have issues.

500
00:19:59.767 --> 00:20:01.464
But are they killers?
I don't know.

501
00:20:01.638 --> 00:20:03.423
Even if they were capable
of killing.

502
00:20:03.597 --> 00:20:06.600
why would they choose tonight
of all nights to do it?

503
00:20:06.861 --> 00:20:08.079
- That's a good question.
- While you two

504
00:20:08.340 --> 00:20:10.386
ponder that.
I have Kasie's laptop

505
00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:11.735
to double-vet
their clearance docs.

506
00:20:11.909 --> 00:20:13.650
Couldn't hurt.
I'll check on Kasie

507
00:20:13.911 --> 00:20:16.174
and call this other custodian
who left early.

508
00:20:16.348 --> 00:20:17.828
And I forget. Jimmy...

509
00:20:18.699 --> 00:20:20.614
...do you have
a couch in your lab?

510
00:20:20.788 --> 00:20:22.659
It's got an autopsy table.

511
00:20:22.833 --> 00:20:25.793
That is close enough.

512
00:20:25.967 --> 00:20:29.144
Oof. He does wear
too much body spray.

513
00:20:29.971 --> 00:20:31.973
- How are the kids. Sam?
- Oh. they're great.

514
00:20:32.147 --> 00:20:33.670
Aiden made captain. as you know.

515
00:20:33.931 --> 00:20:36.281
and Kamran's still on
her mission to save democracy.

516
00:20:36.456 --> 00:20:38.283
Man. they do grow up fast.

517
00:20:38.458 --> 00:20:40.590
You seem to be growing. too.

518
00:20:40.764 --> 00:20:43.288
- You been working out?
- Oh. yeah? Yeah. you can tell?

519
00:20:43.463 --> 00:20:44.942
Hell yeah. Look at Jimmy.

520
00:20:45.116 --> 00:20:46.161
getting buff for the ladies.

521
00:20:46.335 --> 00:20:47.467
I don't know about that. I...

522
00:20:47.641 --> 00:20:48.946
The hell is that?

523
00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:50.470
That's a...

524
00:20:50.644 --> 00:20:52.428
That's a weight vest. Yeah.

525
00:20:52.602 --> 00:20:53.995
30 pounds.

526
00:20:54.256 --> 00:20:55.475
I can see that. Why?

527
00:20:55.649 --> 00:20:56.606
Well. on nights
that I can't sleep.

528
00:20:56.780 --> 00:20:58.390
I come here and I run the steps.

529
00:20:58.608 --> 00:21:02.046
You know. about an hour solid.
up and down every stairwell.

530
00:21:02.917 --> 00:21:04.222
Again. why?

531
00:21:07.399 --> 00:21:09.314
Sam. you ever feel like

532
00:21:09.489 --> 00:21:11.491
you get knocked down
in life so much.

533
00:21:11.665 --> 00:21:14.450
that you're not sure
you can get back up again?

534
00:21:14.624 --> 00:21:16.060
No. Never.

535
00:21:16.496 --> 00:21:17.845
Sam. come on. I'm trying
to open up to you here. What...

536
00:21:18.019 --> 00:21:19.499
Okay. Okay. Jimmy. of course.

537
00:21:19.673 --> 00:21:22.110
That's a part of life. Jimmy.
Of course I do.

538
00:21:22.284 --> 00:21:23.764
What's got you down?

539
00:21:23.938 --> 00:21:25.635
I've been thinking.
ever since I lost Breena.

540
00:21:25.809 --> 00:21:27.463
and then. of course.
Jess and I broke up

541
00:21:27.637 --> 00:21:30.945
and now my daughter
is 14 going on 40...

542
00:21:31.119 --> 00:21:33.556
Man. I feel like it's me
that needs a reboot.

543
00:21:33.730 --> 00:21:35.993
Or a goal. But. like...

544
00:21:36.777 --> 00:21:38.387
Like. a big one.

545
00:21:39.214 --> 00:21:41.259
Okay. What do you have in mind?

546
00:21:41.433 --> 00:21:43.218
Kilimanjaro.

547
00:21:43.392 --> 00:21:45.307
Kilimanjaro?

548
00:21:45.481 --> 00:21:47.614
- Damn. Jimmy.
- Uh. yeah. I-I mean. around here.

549
00:21:47.788 --> 00:21:49.267
Sam. I feel like I've become
a house cat. you know?

550
00:21:49.441 --> 00:21:50.617
I don't want to be a house cat.

551
00:21:50.791 --> 00:21:52.357
I want to be more a. a...

552
00:21:52.532 --> 00:21:53.968
a bobcat.

553
00:21:54.359 --> 00:21:56.448
You climb Kilimanjaro.
you'll be a damn mountain lion.

554
00:21:57.885 --> 00:21:59.190
Good for you. Jimmy.

555
00:21:59.451 --> 00:22:00.757
I love the idea.

556
00:22:00.931 --> 00:22:02.542
I bet everyone else
does. too. huh?

557
00:22:02.803 --> 00:22:04.805
E-Everyone else... yeah. yeah.

558
00:22:04.979 --> 00:22:08.156
Absolutely.
Oh. hey. look at this.

559
00:22:09.026 --> 00:22:11.072
Daryl went to Penn
about the same time Breena did.

560
00:22:11.246 --> 00:22:12.160
I wonder if they knew
each other.

561
00:22:12.334 --> 00:22:13.553
- Penn?
- Yeah.

562
00:22:13.814 --> 00:22:15.511
Harold said they went
to Cornell together.

563
00:22:15.685 --> 00:22:18.340
I knew that was weird.
He even corrected himself

564
00:22:18.514 --> 00:22:19.820
after saying Penn first.

565
00:22:19.994 --> 00:22:22.779
Well. let's look up Harold.

566
00:22:24.476 --> 00:22:25.913
Cornell. Like he said.

567
00:22:26.174 --> 00:22:29.743
Why would he lie about
going there with Daryl?

568
00:22:30.352 --> 00:22:32.049
How about we go ask him?

569
00:22:34.835 --> 00:22:36.097
I never understand lying.

570
00:22:36.271 --> 00:22:37.707
What was it Mark Twain said?

571
00:22:37.881 --> 00:22:39.100
"Just tell the truth

572
00:22:39.404 --> 00:22:40.144
and you don't have
to remember anything."

573
00:22:40.318 --> 00:22:41.929
Hmm.

574
00:22:44.671 --> 00:22:46.281
Okay. fine. I lied.

575
00:22:46.455 --> 00:22:49.327
What?

576
00:22:49.501 --> 00:22:52.069
Uh. no one in the building
loves my Kilimanjaro plan.

577
00:22:52.330 --> 00:22:54.463
because...

578
00:22:55.377 --> 00:22:56.813
...I haven't told anyone yet.

579
00:22:56.987 --> 00:22:59.773
- So. no one else knows?
- Mm-mm.

580
00:23:00.034 --> 00:23:02.123
- And why not?
- Uh. well...

581
00:23:05.126 --> 00:23:06.823
That can't be good.

582
00:23:06.997 --> 00:23:08.477
Not good at all.

583
00:23:08.651 --> 00:23:11.480
No.

584
00:23:19.793 --> 00:23:21.577
Whole building's out.

585
00:23:21.751 --> 00:23:23.361
Generator should keep
the essential lights on

586
00:23:23.535 --> 00:23:24.711
for at least the next few hours.

587
00:23:24.885 --> 00:23:26.626
Along with the reboot.
thank God.

588
00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:28.410
Well. reboot's drinking up
a lot more battery

589
00:23:28.584 --> 00:23:29.803
than what's left of our lights.

590
00:23:29.977 --> 00:23:31.326
so I wouldn't go
celebrating just yet.

591
00:23:31.500 --> 00:23:33.197
All I was trying to do
was plan a nice

592
00:23:33.371 --> 00:23:35.373
little quiet
evening MTAC upgrade

593
00:23:35.547 --> 00:23:37.854
where nothing could possibly
go wrong. and sure enough.

594
00:23:38.028 --> 00:23:39.029
everything's gone wrong.

595
00:23:39.203 --> 00:23:40.944
None of which is a coincidence.

596
00:23:41.118 --> 00:23:42.685
First. one of your tech trolls
gets whacked.

597
00:23:42.859 --> 00:23:44.861
and now a sudden power outage?

598
00:23:45.035 --> 00:23:46.471
And all I was
worried about was hackers.

599
00:23:46.733 --> 00:23:48.256
Well. keep worrying.
I got a feeling

600
00:23:48.430 --> 00:23:50.258
who's ever behind this
is just getting started.

601
00:23:50.432 --> 00:23:51.433
Where are you going?

602
00:23:51.694 --> 00:23:53.261
- To find out who.
- Wait.

603
00:23:55.045 --> 00:23:56.220
Do you smell smoke?

604
00:23:59.963 --> 00:24:01.965
You have got to be kidding me.

605
00:24:03.663 --> 00:24:05.665
Hello? Anyone?

606
00:24:05.839 --> 00:24:07.579
No bars. Parker?

607
00:24:07.754 --> 00:24:10.452
- Hello?
- Yeah. me. either. Kasie?

608
00:24:10.626 --> 00:24:13.629
Sam. what are the odds that this
is just a random blackout?

609
00:24:13.890 --> 00:24:15.718
I'd say slim and none.

610
00:24:15.892 --> 00:24:17.981
Which means we got to get
the hell out of here.

611
00:24:18.155 --> 00:24:20.331
All right. okay. there is
a fireman's key in one of those

612
00:24:20.592 --> 00:24:22.203
- "in case of emergency" boxes.
- Yeah.

613
00:24:22.377 --> 00:24:23.291
It's on the third floor.

614
00:24:23.552 --> 00:24:24.596
Well. we just have to get to it.

615
00:24:24.858 --> 00:24:26.381
- Yeah.
- Whoever designed that hatch

616
00:24:26.555 --> 00:24:27.817
did not have me in mind.

617
00:24:28.078 --> 00:24:29.384
Oh. I don't know. Sam.

618
00:24:29.601 --> 00:24:30.646
I think you could probably
fit through there.

619
00:24:30.820 --> 00:24:32.648
No. no. no. You're gonna do it.

620
00:24:32.822 --> 00:24:34.650
Me? Wait... what do you mean. me?

621
00:24:34.824 --> 00:24:36.957
Why haven't you told anyone
about Kilimanjaro?

622
00:24:37.131 --> 00:24:39.699
I-I don't know. I guess
it just hasn't come up yet.

623
00:24:39.873 --> 00:24:41.135
I don't buy that.

624
00:24:41.309 --> 00:24:42.658
Maybe I'm not ready to share

625
00:24:42.832 --> 00:24:44.007
my workout plans with everyone.

626
00:24:44.181 --> 00:24:45.879
Would you stop? I know you.

627
00:24:46.053 --> 00:24:47.358
All right?
You're probably more worried

628
00:24:47.619 --> 00:24:49.534
about changing your mind.
chickening out.

629
00:24:49.709 --> 00:24:51.580
Wha... hey. I am not
chickening out. all right?

630
00:24:51.754 --> 00:24:54.278
I j... I just don't want to get
everyone's hopes up. you know?

631
00:24:54.452 --> 00:24:57.412
If there's no expectations.
there's no letting anyone down.

632
00:24:57.586 --> 00:24:59.066
Like yourself?

633
00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:01.416
Okay. Sam. but...

634
00:25:01.590 --> 00:25:02.591
There are no buts.

635
00:25:02.765 --> 00:25:04.419
You start telling people. Jimmy.

636
00:25:04.636 --> 00:25:06.943
Don't give yourself an out.
Throw your hat over that wall.

637
00:25:07.117 --> 00:25:10.033
This is your Kilimanjaro moment.
See that? That's Kilimanjaro.

638
00:25:10.207 --> 00:25:11.948
All right. O-Okay. all right.
Fine. fine. Sam.

639
00:25:12.122 --> 00:25:14.342
- I-I. I'll-I'll. I'll tell everyone. all right?
- Yeah?

640
00:25:14.516 --> 00:25:17.649
- Just give me a boost here.
- I'm trying. you're not listening.

641
00:25:17.824 --> 00:25:19.913
- No. I mean. like. a physical
boost. You're a strong person. - Oh.

642
00:25:20.087 --> 00:25:21.436
- I need to get... Yeah.
- Right. No. all right.

643
00:25:21.610 --> 00:25:23.046
Okay. Come on. All right.

644
00:25:23.307 --> 00:25:24.526
All right. You ready?

645
00:25:24.787 --> 00:25:25.614
- All right.
- One...

646
00:25:25.788 --> 00:25:26.876
...two. three.

647
00:25:29.052 --> 00:25:30.750
All right.
come on. come on. Push.

648
00:25:30.924 --> 00:25:32.839
- It's really heavy.
- You're heavy.

649
00:25:33.013 --> 00:25:35.189
Wait a minute. are you still
wearing that damn vest?

650
00:25:35.363 --> 00:25:36.843
I'm still wearing
that damn vest. Yes.

651
00:25:37.104 --> 00:25:38.758
- Come on. come on. come on.
- All right.

652
00:25:38.932 --> 00:25:40.672
Push. Come on. come on.

653
00:25:40.847 --> 00:25:42.936
Push. push. push. There you go.

654
00:25:43.197 --> 00:25:46.548
- There you go. Come on.
- All right.

655
00:25:46.722 --> 00:25:48.550
Come on. come on.
come on. Attaboy.

656
00:25:48.724 --> 00:25:50.030
All right.

657
00:25:51.379 --> 00:25:52.859
Yeah.

658
00:25:54.556 --> 00:25:56.384
Uh. that third floor's
a little higher than I thought.

659
00:25:56.558 --> 00:25:58.560
but. uh. I'll give it a try.

660
00:25:58.734 --> 00:26:00.954
There is no "try." Jimmy.
Just do it.

661
00:26:01.128 --> 00:26:02.520
How's that for a boost?

662
00:26:04.827 --> 00:26:06.089
Come on.

663
00:26:06.263 --> 00:26:07.874
Attaboy. J... Come on. Jimmy.

664
00:26:08.048 --> 00:26:09.789
You got this. Jim.

665
00:26:12.095 --> 00:26:14.358
Ooh. found the smoky culprit.

666
00:26:14.532 --> 00:26:16.317
- Well. what is it?
- Power supply

667
00:26:16.491 --> 00:26:17.884
to the cooling system.

668
00:26:18.058 --> 00:26:21.191
Circa 1997.
from the looks of it.

669
00:26:21.365 --> 00:26:23.150
Blackout must have fried
the motor.

670
00:26:23.324 --> 00:26:24.499
You got a replacement?

671
00:26:26.414 --> 00:26:29.547
With the way this night
has gone. what do you think?

672
00:26:34.857 --> 00:26:36.903
Hang in there. Jimmy.
You got it.

673
00:26:38.687 --> 00:26:40.689
Come on. Jimmy. Attaboy.

674
00:26:46.347 --> 00:26:48.479
Come on. Jimmy!

675
00:26:48.653 --> 00:26:50.394
Okay. uh... Okay.

676
00:26:50.568 --> 00:26:52.266
Um...

677
00:26:52.440 --> 00:26:54.137
I'm not sure
I can reach the door.

678
00:26:54.355 --> 00:26:56.705
I mean. there's-there's nothing
left to-to grab onto here.

679
00:26:56.879 --> 00:26:59.316
Just grab it. Jimmy. Go for it!

680
00:26:59.490 --> 00:27:01.275
Uh. uh...

681
00:27:01.536 --> 00:27:03.973
Sam. I'm not so sure
about my grip.

682
00:27:06.106 --> 00:27:07.324
You know what?
Maybe you're right.

683
00:27:07.498 --> 00:27:09.065
Climbing's hard. Just forget it.

684
00:27:09.239 --> 00:27:11.720
Maybe don't tell anyone
about Kilimanjaro. either.

685
00:27:11.894 --> 00:27:13.853
Just forget it. Forget it.

686
00:27:14.027 --> 00:27:16.333
Let's stay in the elevator.
Come on back down.

687
00:27:25.995 --> 00:27:27.214
That's my man! There you go!

688
00:27:27.388 --> 00:27:29.172
Attaboy. You got this.

689
00:27:31.827 --> 00:27:33.568
Come on. come on. Jimmy!

690
00:27:33.742 --> 00:27:35.570
There you go!

691
00:27:37.572 --> 00:27:39.008
Come on!

692
00:27:40.357 --> 00:27:41.663
There you go. Jimmy.

693
00:27:41.924 --> 00:27:43.752
Now get up. get up there.
You can get it.

694
00:27:43.926 --> 00:27:45.797
Trust it. Jim.

695
00:27:47.234 --> 00:27:48.365
Come on. Jimmy.

696
00:27:52.935 --> 00:27:54.197
There you go.

697
00:27:54.371 --> 00:27:55.764
My man.

698
00:27:55.938 --> 00:27:57.287
Oh. boy.

699
00:27:57.461 --> 00:27:58.506
That was easy.

700
00:27:58.680 --> 00:28:00.029
Here we go. the box.

701
00:28:00.290 --> 00:28:01.335
Uh. ah.

702
00:28:01.509 --> 00:28:02.597
Jackpot.

703
00:28:02.771 --> 00:28:04.033
All right.

704
00:28:04.207 --> 00:28:05.687
Okay.

705
00:28:05.861 --> 00:28:09.125
I can do an elevator shaft.
I can do Kilimanjaro.

706
00:28:09.299 --> 00:28:10.518
Where I won't have to deal
with the dark.

707
00:28:10.692 --> 00:28:12.215
All right. let's see.

708
00:28:12.476 --> 00:28:13.869
All right. so. a key.

709
00:28:14.130 --> 00:28:16.698
I'm guessing these are like
skeleton keys. right?

710
00:28:18.700 --> 00:28:20.310
All right.

711
00:28:21.007 --> 00:28:22.791
All right. Sam?

712
00:28:22.965 --> 00:28:25.359
It's me Jimmy.
Don't shoot. okay?

713
00:28:26.577 --> 00:28:28.492
Hey. Sam.

714
00:28:28.666 --> 00:28:29.885
Found the key and it worked.

715
00:28:30.146 --> 00:28:31.539
Way to go. Mountain Lion.

716
00:28:31.800 --> 00:28:33.976
Way to go. Okay.

717
00:28:34.150 --> 00:28:36.457
- Let's go find Parker.
- Yeah.

718
00:28:38.198 --> 00:28:41.331
So. which is it?
Cornell or Penn?

719
00:28:41.505 --> 00:28:42.767
I'm sorry.
what are you asking me?

720
00:28:42.942 --> 00:28:45.248
No more apologies. Harold.

721
00:28:45.509 --> 00:28:46.858
Daryl's background document
said Penn.

722
00:28:47.033 --> 00:28:48.773
where you said you met him
before "remembering"

723
00:28:48.948 --> 00:28:50.558
you both went to Cornell.

724
00:28:51.428 --> 00:28:54.127
- Okay. a-again. I am so sorry. but...
- Hey.

725
00:28:55.041 --> 00:28:57.347
If you say "sorry"
one more time.

726
00:28:57.521 --> 00:28:59.262
I'm gonna drive you up to Ithaca

727
00:28:59.436 --> 00:29:02.048
and toss you
in one of those gorges.

728
00:29:02.309 --> 00:29:04.006
Okay. look. I'm sorr...

729
00:29:04.180 --> 00:29:05.877
Hey.

730
00:29:07.618 --> 00:29:08.880
Okay. fine.

731
00:29:09.055 --> 00:29:10.795
You got me.

732
00:29:10.970 --> 00:29:14.799
My name isn't Harold.
it's Frank.

733
00:29:15.061 --> 00:29:16.584
And I got kicked out of Penn
after they caught me

734
00:29:16.845 --> 00:29:19.108
hacking into their mainframe
to change my final grade.

735
00:29:19.282 --> 00:29:21.545
Well. that's quite a confession.

736
00:29:21.719 --> 00:29:23.983
but why the identity change?

737
00:29:24.244 --> 00:29:27.769
Like I told Sam. these jobs
really don't grow on trees.

738
00:29:27.943 --> 00:29:29.989
There's no way
I was getting hired after that.

739
00:29:30.163 --> 00:29:34.776
So. I had to become Harold from
Cornell just to get interviews.

740
00:29:35.037 --> 00:29:36.952
Okay. so...

741
00:29:38.345 --> 00:29:40.260
...that's one big lie explained.

742
00:29:40.434 --> 00:29:41.957
Any others?

743
00:29:42.131 --> 00:29:44.090
Like. about Daryl?

744
00:29:44.351 --> 00:29:45.526
Daryl?

745
00:29:45.700 --> 00:29:47.528
No. why? Is he still sick?

746
00:29:48.964 --> 00:29:50.661
Wait. am I in trouble?

747
00:29:51.010 --> 00:29:53.316
- How's it looking?
- It's looking like Harold from Cornell

748
00:29:53.490 --> 00:29:55.057
is actually Frank from Penn.

749
00:29:55.231 --> 00:29:56.928
but neither of them
seem like killers.

750
00:29:57.103 --> 00:29:58.843
And I have no idea
what that that means.

751
00:29:59.105 --> 00:30:00.584
but there's no time
to ask. either.

752
00:30:04.675 --> 00:30:06.025
Stay put.

753
00:30:07.809 --> 00:30:10.246
Yeah. We were wrong
about the PSU.

754
00:30:10.420 --> 00:30:11.943
With about 25 minutes left.

755
00:30:12.118 --> 00:30:13.728
the server's starting
to overheat.

756
00:30:13.945 --> 00:30:15.512
Oh. we'd need an antique shop
to replace that old thing.

757
00:30:15.686 --> 00:30:17.079
Antique computer shop at that.

758
00:30:17.253 --> 00:30:19.908
Hold on. hold on.
What about Old MTAC?

759
00:30:20.082 --> 00:30:22.432
- Old MTAC?
- Our MTAC is old MTAC.

760
00:30:22.606 --> 00:30:25.566
No. no. Vance once showed me
these old NIS MTAC parts

761
00:30:25.740 --> 00:30:27.481
at the evidence locker.
way in the back.

762
00:30:27.742 --> 00:30:29.222
Old MTAC parts. let's go.

763
00:30:29.396 --> 00:30:31.746
Okay. we got about
24 minutes left.

764
00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:33.835
- Hey. where's my laptop?
- Oh. I left it in autopsy.

765
00:30:34.009 --> 00:30:35.706
- I'll have to go get it.
- Okay.

766
00:30:36.577 --> 00:30:38.100
Are they gone?

767
00:30:38.361 --> 00:30:40.450
Yes. Harold. and we've got
a meltdown to prepare for.

768
00:30:40.624 --> 00:30:42.322
All right.
I'll meet you in MTAC.

769
00:30:49.546 --> 00:30:51.200
I see a lot of boxes.

770
00:30:51.374 --> 00:30:53.159
none labeled "MTAC."

771
00:30:53.898 --> 00:30:54.725
Bingo.

772
00:30:54.899 --> 00:30:56.727
I think they were back here.

773
00:31:01.906 --> 00:31:03.212
Damn.

774
00:31:03.473 --> 00:31:04.909
Look at that beast.

775
00:31:05.084 --> 00:31:06.563
Well. believe it or not.

776
00:31:06.737 --> 00:31:09.218
these were once considered
"mini-computers."

777
00:31:09.392 --> 00:31:11.612
Made by "Wang"? Is that real?

778
00:31:11.786 --> 00:31:13.440
Uh. it was.
before they went bankrupt.

779
00:31:13.614 --> 00:31:15.485
With a name like Wang.
no wonder.

780
00:31:15.659 --> 00:31:18.575
Well. let's hope
one of these Wangs has a fan.

781
00:31:20.360 --> 00:31:22.579
So. you said Vance
showed you all this. huh?

782
00:31:22.753 --> 00:31:25.278
Haven't seen you
since the funeral.

783
00:31:25.452 --> 00:31:27.193
How's everybody doing with that?

784
00:31:27.367 --> 00:31:29.151
You know. losing him.

785
00:31:29.325 --> 00:31:31.327
I don't know.
Doesn't seem real.

786
00:31:31.501 --> 00:31:33.460
A lot of us are still in denial.

787
00:31:33.634 --> 00:31:35.462
Yeah. me. too.

788
00:31:35.636 --> 00:31:36.898
Tell you what.

789
00:31:37.072 --> 00:31:40.075
we replace old MTAC
with new MTAC.

790
00:31:40.336 --> 00:31:41.598
but people?

791
00:31:42.469 --> 00:31:43.905
Like Vance?

792
00:31:44.079 --> 00:31:45.950
Not replacing that.

793
00:31:46.125 --> 00:31:48.039
Not a chance.

794
00:31:48.823 --> 00:31:51.173
But it did get me thinking
about where I'm headed.

795
00:31:51.347 --> 00:31:53.567
I've been waiting
to make a move for a while now.

796
00:31:53.741 --> 00:31:58.049
haven't been able to settle
on a direction quite yet.

797
00:31:58.224 --> 00:32:00.356
Well. I know the feeling.

798
00:32:00.530 --> 00:32:02.880
The dreaded Waiting Place.

799
00:32:03.054 --> 00:32:04.708
"A most useless place."

800
00:32:05.666 --> 00:32:06.928
Dr. Seuss.

801
00:32:07.102 --> 00:32:08.973
<i>Oh. the Places You'll Go!</i>

802
00:32:09.148 --> 00:32:10.584
I love that book.

803
00:32:10.758 --> 00:32:12.586
I may have to read it again.

804
00:32:13.891 --> 00:32:15.676
I'm done waiting.

805
00:32:17.112 --> 00:32:18.026
Thank you. Parker.

806
00:32:18.200 --> 00:32:19.810
No worries.

807
00:32:20.724 --> 00:32:21.812
Hello.

808
00:32:22.726 --> 00:32:24.641
Huh? You got it?

809
00:32:24.815 --> 00:32:27.209
Well. it's as old and worn-out
as the other one.

810
00:32:27.383 --> 00:32:28.863
but. uh...

811
00:32:29.037 --> 00:32:30.386
Let's see if it works.

812
00:32:30.560 --> 00:32:32.301
All right. copy that.

813
00:32:32.562 --> 00:32:34.869
- Got it?
- Let's go.

814
00:32:35.696 --> 00:32:37.828
Okay. where's that laptop?

815
00:32:38.699 --> 00:32:40.179
Oh. hey.

816
00:32:40.353 --> 00:32:42.181
There you are.

817
00:32:43.486 --> 00:32:45.314
Oh. God!

818
00:32:45.575 --> 00:32:47.664
You scared me.

819
00:32:48.535 --> 00:32:50.493
What are you doing here?

820
00:33:07.467 --> 00:33:08.685
How we doing under there. Kase?

821
00:33:08.859 --> 00:33:10.600
We? Who's we?

822
00:33:10.905 --> 00:33:13.081
- How are <i>you</i> doing?
- You think that fan's gonna work?

823
00:33:13.255 --> 00:33:15.649
Well. depends. I got it running.

824
00:33:15.823 --> 00:33:17.303
Check the gauge.

825
00:33:17.477 --> 00:33:19.827
Ah. there he is. Finally.

826
00:33:20.001 --> 00:33:22.351
- Looks like the temp is going down.
- Ah. yes.

827
00:33:22.525 --> 00:33:24.179
Then it's working.
Thank you. guys.

828
00:33:24.484 --> 00:33:25.963
- Well. it's working for now. at least.
- Just a few minutes

829
00:33:26.137 --> 00:33:27.443
left. and you're gonna
jinx us now?

830
00:33:27.704 --> 00:33:28.836
I think it's fair to say

831
00:33:29.010 --> 00:33:30.359
your reboot is way past
being jinxed.

832
00:33:30.533 --> 00:33:31.447
You can say that again.

833
00:33:31.621 --> 00:33:33.014
This is Vito. saying

834
00:33:33.232 --> 00:33:35.538
that Tommy wasn't even scheduled
to work tonight.

835
00:33:35.712 --> 00:33:36.626
Vito?

836
00:33:36.800 --> 00:33:37.932
The janitor who went home early.

837
00:33:38.106 --> 00:33:39.499
According to this.

838
00:33:39.716 --> 00:33:42.893
Tommy is who insisted
Vito go home before 1:00.

839
00:33:43.067 --> 00:33:44.678
Before the upgrade started.

840
00:33:44.852 --> 00:33:46.201
Meaning what?

841
00:33:46.462 --> 00:33:48.725
Well. let's go ask him.
And let Jimmy know.

842
00:33:48.899 --> 00:33:50.553
in case
he runs into Tommy before we do.

843
00:33:50.727 --> 00:33:52.251
Where is Jimmy. anyway?

844
00:33:52.425 --> 00:33:53.817
Well. he went
to go get my laptop.

845
00:33:53.991 --> 00:33:55.689
but he should be back by now.

846
00:34:00.041 --> 00:34:02.478
Ah. Tommy. what are...
what are you doing?

847
00:34:02.652 --> 00:34:04.654
Don't get up. Jimmy. please.

848
00:34:04.915 --> 00:34:06.700
Which one is it?
Which one is it?

849
00:34:06.874 --> 00:34:08.005
Which what? What-What's...
what's going on?

850
00:34:08.179 --> 00:34:09.442
The wire. Jimmy.

851
00:34:09.616 --> 00:34:11.531
Which wire patches me
into the reboot?

852
00:34:11.705 --> 00:34:13.620
The reboot?
Uh. that's not exactly...

853
00:34:13.794 --> 00:34:15.448
The mainframe!
Well. whatever the hell that is.

854
00:34:15.709 --> 00:34:18.451
He told me I have to patch into
the reboot on the mainframe.

855
00:34:18.625 --> 00:34:19.800
Which-which wire is it?

856
00:34:19.974 --> 00:34:21.932
Uh. the-the blue one.
The Ethernet.

857
00:34:22.106 --> 00:34:24.544
That should get you
to the mainframe. Tommy.

858
00:34:24.718 --> 00:34:25.980
what... what is going on?

859
00:34:26.197 --> 00:34:28.287
I-I can't explain it right now.
Jimmy.

860
00:34:28.461 --> 00:34:29.810
- I'm sorry.
- Okay. maybe you tell me

861
00:34:30.027 --> 00:34:31.333
what you're trying to do.
and maybe I can help.

862
00:34:31.507 --> 00:34:33.161
- No. no. no. Stay back. Jimmy!
- Whoa. Whoa.

863
00:34:33.335 --> 00:34:35.076
Please. Please.

864
00:34:35.250 --> 00:34:37.339
I have to do this.
Please. Jimmy. Please.

865
00:34:37.600 --> 00:34:39.167
Do what? Tommy. come on.

866
00:34:39.428 --> 00:34:40.690
Just stop asking
so many questions.

867
00:34:40.864 --> 00:34:42.213
I can't explain until it's done.

868
00:34:42.431 --> 00:34:44.999
- Till what's done?
- No. no. no. no. no. no!

869
00:34:45.173 --> 00:34:46.827
- No. No.
- What are you doing. Tommy?

870
00:34:47.001 --> 00:34:48.568
No. Just.

871
00:34:48.742 --> 00:34:50.134
don't make me use this. Parker.

872
00:34:50.439 --> 00:34:51.527
Please. Just. just stay back.

873
00:34:51.701 --> 00:34:53.573
Just. just stay over there. okay?

874
00:34:57.054 --> 00:34:58.534
Is this what you meant
about helping?

875
00:34:58.795 --> 00:35:00.493
Like I'm guessing
you helped Daryl?

876
00:35:00.667 --> 00:35:03.278
That was an accident. I swear.

877
00:35:03.452 --> 00:35:04.932
I couldn't let him stop me.

878
00:35:05.106 --> 00:35:06.542
Why not. Tommy?

879
00:35:06.716 --> 00:35:07.978
Stop you from what?

880
00:35:08.152 --> 00:35:09.415
Don't come any closer.

881
00:35:09.589 --> 00:35:11.199
I got no time to explain.

882
00:35:11.373 --> 00:35:12.374
Come on. come on. come on.

883
00:35:12.548 --> 00:35:14.942
Please. Please.

884
00:35:16.552 --> 00:35:18.728
Oh. come on. Come on. Come on.

885
00:35:18.902 --> 00:35:21.078
Please.

886
00:35:23.037 --> 00:35:24.865
Please?

887
00:35:29.086 --> 00:35:30.349
Yes!

888
00:35:30.523 --> 00:35:33.134
What? What? What?

889
00:35:33.308 --> 00:35:35.223
Don't do that!

890
00:35:35.397 --> 00:35:36.964
Let me go!

891
00:35:37.138 --> 00:35:38.313
Damn. Lion.

892
00:35:38.618 --> 00:35:40.271
Let me go. please.
I'm sorry. Jimmy.

893
00:35:40.446 --> 00:35:42.317
He's gonna kill my family.

894
00:35:42.491 --> 00:35:44.711
Your family? What?

895
00:35:44.972 --> 00:35:46.800
Uh. well...

896
00:35:46.974 --> 00:35:48.584
Who. Tommy?

897
00:35:49.411 --> 00:35:52.240
The guy wore a mask. said he'd
kill 'em all if I didn't do it.

898
00:35:52.414 --> 00:35:54.285
Do what? What is that thing?

899
00:35:54.460 --> 00:35:56.070
He wanted me to plug it
into Kasie's laptop

900
00:35:56.244 --> 00:35:57.419
during the upgrade.

901
00:35:57.680 --> 00:35:59.073
I tried as soon as it started.

902
00:35:59.247 --> 00:36:00.553
but that poor computer kid got

903
00:36:00.814 --> 00:36:02.293
in my way.
I'm so sorry. I just...

904
00:36:02.468 --> 00:36:04.774
- No. no. no. no. no. no!
- Hey! Whoa! Whoa!

905
00:36:04.948 --> 00:36:06.907
Stay still. Tommy.

906
00:36:07.081 --> 00:36:08.822
He's got my family.

907
00:36:09.866 --> 00:36:10.824
Please.

908
00:36:10.998 --> 00:36:13.043
He's got my family!

909
00:36:15.872 --> 00:36:17.570
NCIS!

910
00:36:22.009 --> 00:36:23.532
- I got you.
- Clear.

911
00:36:23.706 --> 00:36:26.666
Kate? Are they still here?

912
00:36:26.840 --> 00:36:28.450
- No?
- No. The guy took my phone

913
00:36:28.711 --> 00:36:30.626
and left a while ago.

914
00:36:30.800 --> 00:36:33.281
Oh. thank God you guys got here.

915
00:36:33.455 --> 00:36:34.413
Everybody's okay.

916
00:36:34.587 --> 00:36:35.805
Just breathe. okay?

917
00:36:36.066 --> 00:36:37.067
Everybody's okay now.

918
00:36:37.328 --> 00:36:39.069
- What about Daddy?
- Is Dad okay?

919
00:36:39.243 --> 00:36:41.681
I'm here. you guys.
Daddy-Daddy's here.

920
00:36:41.855 --> 00:36:43.334
Oh. Tommy.

921
00:36:43.509 --> 00:36:45.162
Come here. Come here. Come here.
Come here. Come here.

922
00:36:50.690 --> 00:36:54.650
Hey. We're gonna need everybody
to step outside

923
00:36:54.911 --> 00:36:56.391
so our medics can check you out.

924
00:36:56.565 --> 00:36:58.828
No. we're okay.

925
00:36:59.002 --> 00:37:00.351
<i>All non-emergency personnel.</i>

926
00:37:00.613 --> 00:37:02.615
<i>please stay clear of the area.</i>

927
00:37:02.876 --> 00:37:04.443
<i>Please stay clear of the area.</i>

928
00:37:04.660 --> 00:37:06.836
Guys. you should go out there
and get checked out. okay?

929
00:37:07.010 --> 00:37:08.534
It's okay. It's okay.

930
00:37:08.795 --> 00:37:11.450
You guys... you guys.
go get checked out. okay?

931
00:37:11.624 --> 00:37:13.669
You guys. I'll be right out. okay?

932
00:37:13.843 --> 00:37:15.018
- Okay. I love you. I love you.
- Okay.

933
00:37:15.192 --> 00:37:17.325
- Daddy's fine.
- I love you so much.

934
00:37:22.156 --> 00:37:24.767
Thank... thank you. guys.
Thank you. guys. Thank you.

935
00:37:24.941 --> 00:37:26.726
It's your turn. Tommy.

936
00:37:26.900 --> 00:37:27.901
Talk to us.

937
00:37:28.075 --> 00:37:30.164
I didn't mean to kill that kid.

938
00:37:30.425 --> 00:37:32.253
He tried to stop me
from getting that laptop.

939
00:37:32.427 --> 00:37:34.908
and I just...
I pulled my elbow back.

940
00:37:35.082 --> 00:37:38.389
Caught him on the chin.
and then he...

941
00:37:38.564 --> 00:37:40.174
he landed...

942
00:37:40.348 --> 00:37:41.784
wrong.

943
00:37:41.958 --> 00:37:44.178
You didn't think
to alert an agent or two?

944
00:37:44.439 --> 00:37:47.442
The guy said that if I told
anyone. they'd be dead.

945
00:37:47.616 --> 00:37:50.750
That if I didn't plant
the device. they'd be dead.

946
00:37:50.924 --> 00:37:52.708
I'm sorry. I panicked.

947
00:37:52.882 --> 00:37:56.016
Well. you seemed calm enough
when Jimmy and I found you.

948
00:37:56.277 --> 00:37:57.757
Well. I wasn't.

949
00:37:57.931 --> 00:38:00.107
I was desperate.
and as time was getting closer.

950
00:38:00.281 --> 00:38:02.283
I killed the power so that I...

951
00:38:04.590 --> 00:38:07.506
I'm sorry. For Jimmy.

952
00:38:07.680 --> 00:38:09.638
For that poor kid.

953
00:38:09.812 --> 00:38:11.684
For the whole thing. I...

954
00:38:11.858 --> 00:38:15.252
I'm just... I-I'm so sorry.

955
00:38:21.563 --> 00:38:24.740
Well. considering what he did to
Daryl. I guess I got off easy.

956
00:38:24.914 --> 00:38:27.047
Tommy sent an apology
for that. too.

957
00:38:27.308 --> 00:38:28.048
Yeah. poor guy.

958
00:38:28.309 --> 00:38:29.571
And poor Daryl.

959
00:38:29.832 --> 00:38:31.965
Poor everybody.
No winners on this one.

960
00:38:32.139 --> 00:38:33.967
Well. Kasie... maybe?

961
00:38:34.141 --> 00:38:35.272
True enough.

962
00:38:35.446 --> 00:38:36.796
Yeah. despite it all.

963
00:38:36.970 --> 00:38:39.059
Kasie pulled off
the big upgrade.

964
00:38:39.320 --> 00:38:40.669
What about Jimmy?

965
00:38:40.930 --> 00:38:42.410
- That epic. WrestleMania takedown.
- Yeah.

966
00:38:42.584 --> 00:38:43.846
That was pretty badass. Jimmy.

967
00:38:44.020 --> 00:38:46.022
Well. you know. I did have

968
00:38:46.196 --> 00:38:48.982
a couple extra pounds on me
to help take him down.

969
00:38:49.156 --> 00:38:51.637
Couple extra pounds?
What are you talking about?

970
00:38:51.898 --> 00:38:55.118
I'm wearing
a 30-pound weight vest.

971
00:38:55.945 --> 00:39:00.123
And you just happened
to be wearing that for... what?

972
00:39:00.297 --> 00:39:01.690
Uh...

973
00:39:01.864 --> 00:39:04.127
Yeah. Jimmy. What's it for?

974
00:39:07.043 --> 00:39:10.307
I am training to hike
Mount Kilimanjaro in the fall.

975
00:39:10.569 --> 00:39:13.528
Or maybe January.
when it's warmer there.

976
00:39:13.702 --> 00:39:15.791
What do you think of that. huh?

977
00:39:15.965 --> 00:39:18.054
Yeah. Huh.

978
00:39:18.228 --> 00:39:22.145
Well. not what I expected
to hear. but. uh...

979
00:39:22.406 --> 00:39:24.017
good for you. Jimmy.

980
00:39:24.191 --> 00:39:27.629
If anybody can make a climb
like that.

981
00:39:27.803 --> 00:39:29.196
it's you.

982
00:39:30.066 --> 00:39:32.547
Guess I just threw my hat
over the wall.

983
00:39:32.721 --> 00:39:34.549
Damn straight.

984
00:39:35.724 --> 00:39:38.031
Again. I am so grateful

985
00:39:38.205 --> 00:39:40.511
for all that we were able
to accomplish tonight.

986
00:39:40.686 --> 00:39:42.644
I know it was obviously

987
00:39:42.818 --> 00:39:44.994
overshadowed by what happened
to Daryl. but...

988
00:39:45.168 --> 00:39:46.909
<i>- I'm never eating donuts again.
- I mean.</i>

989
00:39:47.083 --> 00:39:48.519
<i>I'm sorry. Who dies of
food poisoning anymore?</i>

990
00:39:48.694 --> 00:39:51.087
<i>Can anyone say co-morbidity?</i>

991
00:39:51.261 --> 00:39:53.524
Maybe we can talk about this
during dinner next week.

992
00:39:53.699 --> 00:39:56.179
We'll do a little something
in Daryl's memory.

993
00:39:56.440 --> 00:39:57.790
<i>I have some food restrictions.</i>

994
00:39:58.051 --> 00:39:59.313
<i>Yeah. Maybe no sushi.</i>

995
00:39:59.487 --> 00:40:01.010
<i>Yeah. No sushi. no donuts.</i>

996
00:40:01.228 --> 00:40:02.795
Discuss that among yourselves
and get back to me.

997
00:40:02.969 --> 00:40:05.406
Oh. gosh.

998
00:40:05.580 --> 00:40:07.277
So they still think
it's food poisoning?

999
00:40:07.451 --> 00:40:10.890
You know. the worst part
of lying is having to admit it.

1000
00:40:11.064 --> 00:40:12.326
I'll tell them the truth
during dinner.

1001
00:40:12.500 --> 00:40:14.023
Well. in the meantime.

1002
00:40:14.197 --> 00:40:15.721
how about we all go out
and have an early breakfast?

1003
00:40:15.895 --> 00:40:17.548
Uh. no. you guys.
uh. you go without me.

1004
00:40:17.723 --> 00:40:19.899
I'm just... I'm not hungry.

1005
00:40:20.726 --> 00:40:23.076
What's up. Kase?
You all right?

1006
00:40:23.250 --> 00:40:25.687
What's wrong?

1007
00:40:26.993 --> 00:40:28.559
Whatever Tommy did. it worked.

1008
00:40:28.734 --> 00:40:30.126
Worked how?

1009
00:40:30.300 --> 00:40:31.911
I thought
we stopped him in time.

1010
00:40:32.085 --> 00:40:33.826
Yeah. I did. too. but...

1011
00:40:34.740 --> 00:40:36.350
Since I keep my personal data

1012
00:40:36.524 --> 00:40:37.960
on my laptop.
for security purposes.

1013
00:40:38.134 --> 00:40:40.136
I keep my encryption key
on our mainframe.

1014
00:40:40.310 --> 00:40:43.096
which is why Tommy had to attach
that device during the reboot.

1015
00:40:43.270 --> 00:40:45.315
- When the firewalls were down.
- One would assume

1016
00:40:45.489 --> 00:40:47.796
that whoever forced Tommy
to do it was looking

1017
00:40:47.970 --> 00:40:49.580
for a back door to our database.

1018
00:40:49.755 --> 00:40:51.713
you know.
case files. employee info.

1019
00:40:51.887 --> 00:40:53.149
But they weren't?

1020
00:40:53.497 --> 00:40:54.934
No. none of those folders
were even touched.

1021
00:40:55.108 --> 00:40:57.588
And what they did touch.
you don't see.

1022
00:40:57.763 --> 00:40:59.416
Edna.

1023
00:40:59.590 --> 00:41:00.591
Edna?

1024
00:41:00.766 --> 00:41:02.115
Who's Edna?

1025
00:41:02.289 --> 00:41:05.727
Well. Edna's not a who.
she's a what.

1026
00:41:06.815 --> 00:41:08.817
And she's gone.

1027
00:41:11.559 --> 00:41:14.083
So. this was never
about hacking the upgrade.

1028
00:41:14.257 --> 00:41:17.478
No. No. it was all about Edna.

1029
00:41:17.652 --> 00:41:20.655
Okay. What's Edna?

1030
00:41:20.829 --> 00:41:23.310
What are you saying. Kase?

1031
00:41:23.484 --> 00:41:26.269
I'm saying that I think

1032
00:41:26.443 --> 00:41:29.533
I'm the reason
why Daryl is dead.

1033
